article.description: Michelle Snow and Janeth Arcain combined for 20 points in the second half to help the Houston Comets rally from a 13-point deficit and beat the Miami Sol 53-46 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Snow's best game as pro helps Comets rally
article.linkText: Comets rally from 13 down to beat Sol
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Michelle Snow and Janeth Arcain combined for 20 points in the second half to help the Houston Comets rally from a 13-point deficit and beat the Miami Sol 53-46 Tuesday night. Sheryl Swoopes added 16 points for the Comets (7-3), who have won five of six. Snow finished with career-highs of 11 points and seven rebounds, and Arcain had 11 points. Ruth Riley, still playing with a splint protecting her broken right pinkie, and Sheri Sam both had 11 points for Miami (2-6), which shot 25 percent from the field in the second half in losing for the first time in three games. "I don't think at any point we felt like we were out of it,'' Swoopes said. "We kind of took a lot of pride in who we are and said we weren't going to go down like this. The second half was definitely a different ballgame.'' Just as they did last year when visiting Miami, the Comets established a franchise record for first-half scoring futility. Houston missed 13 of 15 shots in one stretch and finished the half with 16 points, one fewer than it managed last July 20 against the Sol. The Comets then outscored Miami 37-19 in the second half. "To come back and win the game, especially on the road, is big,'' Comets coach Van Chancellor said. "We pulled off a big win.'' Sam's jumper 30 seconds into the second half gave Miami a 29-16 lead, but Houston responded with a turnover-fueled 13-0 run over the next three minutes, capped by a three-point play by Arcain that tied the game at 29. "The baskets we were giving up were easy ones,'' Riley said. "After they evened the game up, we took a step back.'' Betty Lennox's 3-pointer gave Miami its last lead, 39-38, with 7:58 remaining. After that, Snow scored seven of Houston's next eight points as the Comets pulled away. The Sol got within 50-46 after Sam scored with 1:01 remaining, but Houston reserve guard Coquese Washington buried a 3-pointer with 38 seconds left to seal the win. "The biggest play of the game was when Coquese nailed the 3 at the end,'' Swoopes said.

Game notes
Houston's previous low for first-half scoring this season was 20 points, set June 1 at Cleveland in a game the Comets also won. ... Houston outrebounded Miami 22-14 in the second half. ... Trisha Stafford-Odom, signed by the Sol on Monday, was in uniform but did not play. She averaged 3.8 points and 2.8 rebounds in 2001 for Houston, which waived the forward before this season.
